Problem Statement



Benjamin is managing a product inventory for a multi-store business. Each product has multiple price listings from different stores. Benjamin needs to find the lowest price for each product that is available in more than one store. 



Your task is to help Benjamin by writing a program to compute these minimum prices.

Input format :
The first line of input contains an integer n, representing the number of price entries.

Each of the next n lines contains the following space-separated values:

An integer representing the product ID.
An integer representing the store ID (not used in computation, but helps identify different stores).
One or more integers representing the prices of the product in that store.
Output format :
The output prints a dictionary in the format:

{product_id1: min_price1, product_id2: min_price2, ..., product_idN: min_priceN}

Each key is a product_id that has been listed in more than one store (i.e., has more than one price in total across all entries).

Each value is the minimum price for that product across all stores.

The dictionary is printed using standard Python syntax.



Important Conditions Reflected in Output:

A product_id will only appear in the output if it has more than one price entry (i.e., len(prices) > 1).

If a product appears in only one line with one price, or if all its prices come from a single line and there is only one price, it is excluded from the output.

The order of keys in the output dictionary will follow the order in which they were first completely formed in product_prices.



Refer to the sample output for formatting specifications.

Code constraints :
1 ≤ n ≤ 15

101 ≤ productID ≤ 210

1 ≤ store_number ≤ 3

1 ≤ prices ≤ 5000

Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
3
101 1 1200 1100
101 2 1150
201 1 850 800
Output 1 :
{101: 1100, 201: 800}
Input 2 :
4
101 1 1300 1250
101 2 1200
201 1 900 850
201 1 600
Output 2 :
{101: 1200, 201: 600}

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

n = int(input().strip())
product_prices = {}

for _ in range(n):
    parts = list(map(int, input().strip().split()))
    product_id = parts[0]
    prices = parts[2:]  # skip store ID
    
    if product_id in product_prices:
        product_prices[product_id].extend(prices)
    else:
        product_prices[product_id] = prices

# Filter products with more than one price and compute minimum
result = {pid: min(prices) for pid, prices in product_prices.items() if len(prices) > 1}

print(result)
